	id="Exmpl_PartialSum">
	<title>Partial Sums of a Series: Examples</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para><b>Partial sums of a constant series</b> &nbsp; The first five partial sums of the constant series with summands equal to <latex>3</latex> are</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
\begin{array}{rcl}
s_0 & = & 3 \\
s_1 & = & 3 + 3 = 6 \\
s_2 & = & 3 + 3 + 3 = 9 \\
s_3 & = & 3 + 3 + 3 + 3 = 12 \\
s_4 & = & 3 + 3 + 3 + 3 + 3 = 15 \\
s_n & = & (n+1)\cdot 3
\end{array}
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
		</block>
		
		<block>
			<para><b>Partial sums of the harmonic series</b> &nbsp; The first five partial sums of the harmonic series are</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
\begin{array}{rcl}
s_1 & = & 1 \\
s_2 & = & 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} = \dfrac{3}{2} \\
s_3 & = & 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{3} = \dfrac{11}{6} \\
s_4 & = & 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{3} + \dfrac{1}{4} = \dfrac{25}{12} \\
s_5 & = & 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{3} + \dfrac{1}{4} + \dfrac{1}{5} = \dfrac{137}{60}
\end{array}
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
		</block>
		
		<block>
			<para><b>Partial sums of a geometric series</b> &nbsp; The first five partial sums of the geometric series associated to <latex>r\neq 1/2</latex> are</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
\begin{array}{rcl}
s_0 & = & 1 \\
s_1 & = & 1+ \dfrac{1}{2} = \dfrac{3}{2} \\
s_2 & = & 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{4} = \dfrac{7}{4} \\
s_3 & = & 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{4} + \dfrac{1}{8} = \dfrac{15}{8} \\
s_4 & = & 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{4} + \dfrac{1}{8} + \dfrac{1}{16} =  \dfrac{31}{16}
\end{array}
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>For a geometric series with <latex>r\neq 1</latex>, we are lucky: it is possible to write out the <latex>n</latex>-th partial sum using a simple formula:
				<index.glossary>
					<term>geometric</term><term>series</term><term>partial sum</term>
					<info>
						<para>The <latex>n</latex>-th partial sum of the geometric series is</para>
						<math.display>
							<latex>s_n = \sum_{k=0}^{n} r^k = \dfrac{1-r^{k+1}}{1-r}</latex>
						</math.display>
					</info>
				</index.glossary>
			</para>
			<computation>
				<left>s_n</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>1 + r+ r^2 + r^3 + \cdots + r^n</right>
				<left></left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>(1 + r+ r^2 + r^3 + \cdots + r^n)\cdot \dfrac{1-r}{1-r}</right>
				<left></left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>\dfrac{1-r^{n+1}}{1-r}</right>
			</computation>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>